dan added on 2013-11-12 11:51:45:
When processing a LEFT JOIN, the data sources to the left and right of the join may not be reordered. In other words, "t1 LEFT JOIN t2" must be implemented with "t1" as the outer loop. This is not the case with other joins, where SQLite is free to reorder the nesting of loops.
However, it ignores this for virtual tables. For example:
SQLite version 3.8.2 2013-11-12 01:11:56
Enter ".help" for instructions
Enter SQL statements terminated with a ";"
sqlite> CREATE TABLE t1(a);
sqlite> CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE t2 USING rtree(b, x1,x2);
sqlite> EXPLAIN QUERY PLAN SELECT a, b FROM t1 LEFT JOIN t2 ON (+a = +b);
0|0|1|SCAN TABLE t2 VIRTUAL TABLE INDEX 2:
0|1|0|SCAN TABLE t1
sqlite>
